Description: Digital photograph (colour); view of engraved rock art on a boulder, showing three giraffe figures and that of one unidentified quadruped carnivore (jackal? dog?), all pecked and infilled, upright and facing right. The largest giraffe is in the centre, flanked by a slightly smaller one to the left and a much smaller (calf) to the right. All giraffes have long tails, clearly delineated horns and ears and a third horn (possibly median ossicones, mid-facial horn-like protuberances found in northern species of giraffe). The two larger giraffes have flat, forward-pointing (anthropomorphic?) feet. The small carnivore is depicted with legs outstretched as if running toward the largest giraffe, which it is just to the left of. Wadi Hamra, Egypt. Scanned
Curator's comments: Wadi Hamra is a canyon-like valley with a relatively flat floor between one and 200m wide, curling more or less south into the Gilf Kebir plateau in Egypt’s Western Desert. There are three known rock art sites, all for engravings and first reported by Has Rhotert in 1952: The first is an old river terrace with numerous engravings of giraffe and a few of ostrich, cattle and abstract fan-shaped grooves, with stone circles and shallow depressions on the top. The second is several engravings further southwest. The third stands opposite the branch containing the first site: a rocky outcrop about 15 m high with a number of engravings along the base.
Acquisition name: Donated by: Trust for African Rock Art
